      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":30,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":450,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute brisk walk to ease into movement. Let your breathing settle before you begin running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, conversational pace. You should be able to speak in full sentences. If you feel breathless, slow down or take a short walk break — that is not a setback, it is smart training.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease back to a walk for the final 5 minutes. Finish with light stretching of calves, quads, and hips.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute brisk walk before you start running. This primes your cardiovascular system and warms up your leg muscles gradually.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes after finishing. Stretch your calves, hip flexors, and quads gently — hold each stretch for 20–30 seconds without bouncing.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This is your foundational aerobic run for the week. At this stage of your training, easy runs are doing the most important work: building your aerobic base, strengthening connective tissue, and teaching your body to run efficiently. The pace range of 7:00–8:00 per km is intentional — it might feel almost too easy, and that is exactly right. Aerobic adaptation happens at low intensity. Resist the urge to push harder. If you finish feeling like you could have done more, that means it worked perfectly.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Midweek Easy Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":4,\"target_duration_minutes\":32,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":450,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":390,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5-minute brisk walk to warm up before you begin running.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":18,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":450,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at your easy conversational pace. Focus on relaxed shoulders, light footfall, and steady breathing.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":390,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second gentle accelerations (strides) with 40 seconds of easy walking between each. These are not sprints — think of them as smooth, controlled pick-ups where you gradually accelerate to about 80% effort and then ease back down. They teach your legs to move a little faster without taxing your aerobic system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes. Shake out your legs and do light stretching.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"5-minute brisk walk before running. On this day you will include a few short strides at the end of your easy run, so make sure your legs feel properly warmed up before those.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes after the strides. Your legs may feel pleasantly activated — that is normal. Stretch calves, hip flexors, and hamstrings gently.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"This midweek run has a small but meaningful addition: four short strides at the end. Strides are brief, smooth accelerations that introduce your neuromuscular system to faster running without creating fatigue. For a 5K goal, you will eventually need to run at a pace faster than your easy pace — strides begin building that capacity gently and safely. They also improve your running economy, meaning you will use less energy at any given pace over time. Keep them relaxed and controlled; this is not about going all-out.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Run — Building Endurance\",\"target_distance_km\":6,\"target_duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":465,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":465,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Begin with a 5-minute brisk walk. On long run days, this warm-up walk is especially important — it prepares your joints and muscles for sustained effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":35,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":465,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Run at a comfortable, easy pace — slightly slower than your Monday run is perfectly fine. The goal is time on feet, not speed. Walk breaks are completely welcome if needed; aim for a run-walk pattern like 5 minutes running, 1 minute walking if the full distance feels challenging. You are building your aerobic engine today.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":480,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Walk for 5 minutes to bring your heart rate down gradually. Hydrate well and do a thorough stretch — calves, quads, hamstrings, and hips.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start with a 5-minute walk. Drink some water before you head out. Wear comfortable shoes and dress for the weather — your comfort matters on longer efforts.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk for at least 5 minutes after finishing. Rehydrate. Stretch thoroughly, spending extra time on your calves and hips. Consider a short foam roll if you have one available.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your long run is the cornerstone of 5K preparation. It might seem counterintuitive — why run long for a short race? The answer is aerobic base. A stronger aerobic engine means you can sustain your 5K pace with less effort, recover faster between runs, and reduce your injury risk. At 6 km this week, you are progressing thoughtfully from your current 5 km long run — a modest, safe step up. The pace should feel genuinely easy; if you are breathing hard, slow down. Time on feet matters far more than pace on this day. Run-walk intervals are a legitimate, effective strategy — not a compromise.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
